def: Having the form of a lance.
A military punishment formerly practiced, which consisted indrawing an offender to the top of a beam and letting him fall to thelength of the rope, by which means a limb was often dislocated. Shak.
Pertaining to, or derived from camphor. [R.]
To be convereted into a powder or friable substance, or into acalx, by the action of heat. "Calcining without fusion" Newton.
The state or condition of being nonresident, Swift.
A wailing; lamentation. [Obs.] "Ejulation in the pangs ofdeath." Philips.
Belonging to a legion; consisting of a legion or legions, or ofan indefinitely great number; as, legionary soldiers; a legionaryforce. "The legionary body of error." Sir T. Browne.
